vectorData.altText: 13. What is the cutaneous distribution of the ulnar nerve?
That's right! The ulnar nerve innervates the medial hand and one-and-a-half digits (D).
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

As you know, the major branches of the brachial plexus carry sensory fibres as well as motor fibres. Each of them has a region of skin in the upper arm for which they are responsible. Since they are compound nerves, their area of distribution include portions of multiple dermatomes.
The axillary nerve monitors the skin of the lateral aspect of the shoulder.
The radial nerve monitors the skin of the posterior arm, forearm and lateral hand.
The musculocutaneous nerve monitors the skin of the lateral forearm.
The median nerve monitors the skin of the palmar surface of the hand and lateral three and a half digits.
The ulnar nerve innervates the medial hand and one-and-a-half digits.
